Think of it as a **full hackathon flow**, hereâ€™s a clear outline of the pages and their purpose: ---------- ### 1. **Landing Page (Entry Point)** - Public-facing - Purpose: attract participants, explain event, registration - Key elements: - Hackathon name / branding - About / problem statements / tracks - Registration buttons / team formation - Countdown to start (optional) ---------- ### 2. **Dashboard Page (Participant Portal)** - Private, after login/registration - Purpose: track progress, stay updated, participate in real time - Key elements: - **Header**: Hackathon title, team code, logout - **Upper div / quick actions**: notifications, guidelines, round info - **Sidebar Left**: problem statement / solution toggle + mentor calls - **Main**: timer (countdown or stopwatch), progress stepper - **Sidebar Right**: todos / submission form + team chat - **Footer / bottom**: current leaderboard - Repeatable for each round; adapt main timer and stepper per round ---------- ### 3. **"Ended / Summary" Page** - Purpose: showcase hackathon outcomes - Key elements: - **Gallery**: photos/videos of hackathon activities - **Final Leaderboard**: team rankings with scores - **Project Submissions**: links, brief description, downloadable files - **Certificates**: download links or verification for participants - **Prizes / Rewards**: top teams, sponsors, awards - **Testimonials / Feedback**: participants, mentors, sponsors ---------- ### Optional Additions - **Round-specific micro-pages**: if you want to deep-dive into each round - **Notifications / announcements panel**: global updates for participants - **Sponsor / partner showcase**: in landing or summary page ----------
